// Package cm (container manager) provides the kubelet's container-level resource
// management capabilities. It is responsible for managing cgroups, enforcing QoS
// policies, and coordinating compute resource allocation across containers and pods.
//
// # Key Responsibilities
//
// The container manager handles the following core responsibilities:
//
//   - Cgroup Management: Creates, updates, and destroys cgroups for pods and
//     containers. Supports both cgroup v1 and cgroup v2 hierarchies through
//     the CgroupManager interface. On Linux, cgroup controllers manage CPU,
//     memory, pids, and hugepages resources.
//
//   - QoS Enforcement: Implements Kubernetes QoS classes (Guaranteed, Burstable,
//     BestEffort) through the QOSContainerManager. Creates per-QoS cgroup
//     hierarchies when CgroupsPerQOS is enabled, ensuring resource isolation
//     between QoS tiers.
//
//   - Node Allocatable: Enforces node-level resource reservations for system
//     daemons (SystemReserved), Kubernetes components (KubeReserved), and
//     eviction thresholds. The remaining capacity is the Node Allocatable
//     available for pods.
//
//   - Resource Allocation: Coordinates allocation of CPU, memory, and devices
//     to containers through integration with resource managers (cpumanager,
//     memorymanager, devicemanager, topologymanager).
//
// # Key Interfaces
//
// ContainerManager is the primary interface that the kubelet uses to interact
// with container-level resource management. It provides methods for:
//   - Starting container management and housekeeping tasks
//   - Creating PodContainerManager instances for pod-level cgroup management
//   - Retrieving node capacity, allocatable resources, and QoS container info
//   - Managing device plugin resources and dynamic resource allocation (DRA)
//   - Coordinating with topology-aware resource managers
//
// CgroupManager provides low-level cgroup operations including Create, Destroy,
// Update, and resource configuration. It abstracts the differences between
// cgroup v1 and v2 implementations.
//
// PodContainerManager handles pod-level cgroup lifecycle, ensuring pods run
// within their designated cgroup hierarchy with appropriate resource limits.
//
// QOSContainerManager maintains the QoS cgroup hierarchy and periodically
// updates resource constraints based on running pods.
//
// InternalContainerLifecycle provides hooks for container lifecycle events,
// allowing resource managers to allocate and deallocate resources as containers
// start and stop.
//
// # Subpackages
//
// The cm package coordinates several specialized resource managers:
//
//   - cpumanager: Manages CPU affinity for containers requesting exclusive CPUs.
//     Implements static and none policies for CPU pinning decisions.
//
//   - memorymanager: Manages memory and hugepages NUMA affinity. Implements
//     static policy for memory pinning to NUMA nodes.
//
//   - topologymanager: Coordinates topology-aware resource allocation across
//     CPU, memory, and device managers. Provides hints to align resources
//     on the same NUMA node when possible.
//
//   - devicemanager: Implements the device plugin framework, managing external
//     devices (GPUs, FPGAs, etc.) advertised by device plugins. Handles device
//     allocation, health monitoring, and topology hints.
//
//   - dra: Implements Dynamic Resource Allocation for structured parameters,
//     enabling fine-grained resource sharing and allocation through the
//     ResourceClaim API.
//
//   - admission: Provides pod admission handlers that verify resource
//     availability before pod scheduling.
//
// # Platform Considerations
//
